SaharaReporters had last week reported that five of Bwacha’s co-aspirants threatened to boycott the fresh primaries citing irregularities from the APC National Chairman, Abdullahi Adamu A former Chief of Army Staff, Lt Gen Tukur Buratai (retd.) superintended a controversial All Progressives Congress governorship primary in Taraba State and declared Senator Emmanuel Bwacha as the winner of the prmary. On February 1, 2023, leading a five-member Supreme Court panel, Justice Kudirat Kekere-Ekun had nullified Bwacha's initial nomination. SaharaReporters had last week reported that five of Bwacha’s co-aspirants threatened to boycott the fresh primaries citing irregularities from the APC National Chairman, Abdullahi Adamu, the militarisation of the process by engaging Buratai to head the electoral committee. The party, however conducted the fresh primary election where Bwacha was pronounced by the Electoral Committee chairman, Buratai on Friday night. The party, however conducted a fresh primary election where Bwacha defeated five other contestants to clinch the coveted APC gubernatorial ticket as pronounced by the Electoral Committee chairman, Buratai on Friday night. Bwacha who represents the Southern senatorial district of the state polled 778 of the total 791 votes cast by the delegates. Declaring the results, Buratai said, the Senator representing Taraba Central, Yusuf Yusuf, who came second polled only five votes while David Kente, Danladi Kifasi, Saleh Mamman and Senator Anthony Manzo recorded zero votes. In a post victory interface with journalists, Bwacha said "the outcome of the fresh primary election shows that I'm not only popular in the party but also cherished by the delegates. "With this victory, the era of APC being in the opposition is over, because I would defeat my opponents during the governorship election."